\n      \"objectives\": [\n        \"Coordinate with Sela Tidecount, Jaxin Brail, and Vara Rootlight to time the climb and the gate opening.\",\n        \"Pluck the seven chords at their marked links in the correct sequence without being knocked free by wind or lightning.\",\n        \"Signal the Heartward Engine team to close the gate at the final note and record the pulse settling.\",\n        \"Survive the backwash of power and see whether the city’s bones stop singing.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Rhy Tidesong\", \"lines\": \"You will be my hand where my feet cannot go, Sere Kallin, and I will be your breath when the sky tries to steal it. Measure your heart against the Engine’s metronome we practiced, and if panic presses, let the breath be longer than the fear. If the chords begin to argue with one another, do not strike them harder; slow them with kindness until each remembers its place at the table. The heart is old and proud, but it sleeps better to lullabies than to orders, and it will forgive a hesitant note sooner than it forgives a command barked like a Warden’s drill. Leave iron far from your thoughts and hands when you touch those links, and let your voice, even unspoken, be a promise that nothing cruel comes up the chain tonight. Trust that I am below with the gate open and listening, and if you falter, I will lend you a measure and a prayer to make the next reach feel like coming home.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Sela Tidecount\", \"lines\": \"Feel the rope hum and you will know which way the wind is already leaning, because wind talks first to cord and then to skin. Do not fight the gusts like they insulted your mother; roll your shoulder into them and let them think they’ve won while your feet keep climbing where only you know. When I call three short and one long, the gust is a bully and you should hug the iron like a friend only until it passes, and when I sing a flat note you will find the next handhold where you least expect it. If you hear me curse, it is a good sign; it means I still have breath and the chain has not yet taught me new words. Watch for sky swift nests tucked under the third link and do not kick at them, because they know the old currents better than our charts. And if the lantern goes green-blue-green-blue-green, that is my way of saying wait a heartbeat and then trust the drop, because the air has a hand ready to lift you.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Jaxin Brail\", \"lines\": \"The coil is primed and the whistle remembers the last thunder like a sweet tooth that aches when rain thinks of falling. I have tuned the stormglass to the Engine’s measure, and if I tell you to wait one heartbeat before the next note, trust that my fear is doing math faster than my courage can admit. Lightning is a conversationalist when treated with respect, and it will answer the right question with a step to the left instead of a strike to the heart. If this works, we will not hear victory as a shout or a cheer; we will hear the absence of panic, and in that quiet you will feel your bones loosen like hands unclenching. Should a hum come out sour, do not be ashamed of a second pluck gentled by breath; glass forgives more than men do, and the sky is closer to glass today than it is to iron. I will keep my hands steady even if my voice trembles, and I will count for you when the wind tries to turn numbers into noise.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Vara Rootlight\", \"lines\": \"I will keep the water listening without asking it to answer, and I will braid my hymn between wave and link so the sea does not grow jealous of the sky’s song. If you slip, I will do all I can to make the river softer than it knows how to be, but I would rather sing for a climbing friend than a falling one, so let us agree that you will not fall. The Mother of Eels has ears in every rivulet, and I have bartered for her patience with bone and breath; she will keep the eel packs away from your shadow if you keep your shadow kind. There are songs that only climb, and you have one of them in your hands now, so treat each note like a rung carved from trust. When the final chord comes, I will pull the tide taut like a bed-sheet and lay it smooth, and in that hush you will know it is safe to let go and come back to us. And if fear comes up to gnaw at your hands, spit it into the water and I will drown it for you by name.\"}\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\"id\": \"11A\", \"title\": \"Dusk Ascent on the First Hum\", \"text\": \"Sere gathers the team at the basalt foot when the chain’s out-of-season murmur first ripples the air like a cat’s purr, committing to climb at dusk when light is thin but not yet treacherous. She orders the eel-skin coil double-looped and has Sela read the flag-talk of gusts while Jaxin primes the stormglass to sing one breath ahead of lightning. Vara wades to knee and then thigh in brine, setting a wide, low hymn that tucks the waves under the iron like obedient dogs. Sere tests the first handhold with the old Warden habit of tapping twice, then climbs as if each link were a promise she had made and now must keep. Above, the city smolders with lamp-light, and every glance downward is a reminder that this song is bigger than her lungs and older than her scars.\", \"outcome\": \"The dusk winds prove honest and the first three chords answer like well-loved strings, each pluck thinning the static growl in the clouds until thunder sounds like footsteps walking away. At the fourth link a cross-gust tries to pry Sere free, but Sela’s green-blue-green signal buys a heartbeat for Jaxin to murmur a correction and for Sere to lean into the shove with a grin that feels like defiance. Vara’s hymn rounds the rock, laps the barnacles, and turns a biting surge into a soft slap of foam, and even the sky swifts hold their nests steady as if they, too, were listening. The seventh chord lands clean, the Heartward Engine hears its name spoken gently, and Rhy’s 